The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and issued a brochure
Women who are labeled witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They are more likely to be of the older generation, they do not find work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
If one of these women "becomes" a witch, she will be strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
"Men are quite rarely affected by this fate."
“It also saves young and healthy women from having to help in their work and giving birth,” one religious sister describes the situation in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, which takes care of more than one hundred women who have been expelled from their communities in a special home.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, he published a brochure that aims to prevent the "witch persecution".
But there's a catch.
“More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” the newspaper “derStandard” pointed out the dilemma of the written enlightenment.
But witchcraft is also commonplace in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighbouring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahov<0xC3><0xA1> was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured petroleum on her and just set her on fire.
The incident was also reported by the BBC.
The perpetrators, however, claimed that the case was only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to her version, oil is inflamed, which is used for ritual anointings.
That is, after the group had tried to "exorcise an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" supports the people here regardless of their education.
“The Standard” quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: “Eaters of human souls are a danger in the past as they are today,” he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, the Gambian president last year the president himself has been quite involved.
President Yahya Jammeh ignited a monstrous witch hunt after the death of his aunt, as they allegedly had a part in their deaths and would now try to kill the president himself by black magic.
“To this end, he called on the aid of shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the President’s bodyguard, forcibly kidnapped women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the President’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
