The architects saw a - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, whose studios are home to a number of well-known Brno buildings, counted on the premises for its company mini-kindergarten from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building.
Wisely foresighted, because most of its 90 employees (inside) are of the baby boom age and the company is committed to ensuring that the project planners and architects return to their jobs as quickly as possible.
Along with the opportunity to work shorter, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for civil engineers and architects to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The mini kindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company’s mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (grants of CZK 2.8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment were procured and qualified personnel and operations were provided for a period of 2 years.
After the exploitation of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the mini kindergarten for another 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took an entire year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of applications.
The children are taken care of all day by qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children are allowed to be present at the same time, but the day is alternated by several children.
The kindergarten is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in terms of the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it concerns individual education and care, the program content in the mini kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, while they also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and so the stress of picking up the children from a far away kindergarten is eliminated.
Therefore, parents use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also developing here.
Arch.Design was thus one of the Czech companies that offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> by the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile shards and mosaics, the shed-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only on closer inspection that one notices that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and well-thought-out order.
At night, the whole fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade looks even more plastic, more dramatic and the special illumination enhances the brilliance of the colors even more.
The same sweeping lines and intricate shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and ledges.
The Batll<0xC3><0xB3> house in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia No. 43 was built by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese in 1877.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new one, but ultimately he agreed to Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
He collaborated with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was precisely on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner were created and the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other sculptors and artists also participated in the design of the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
For example, Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Shortly after its completion, the house received the nickname "bone house" from the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others, in turn, called it the "yawning house" because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed a central heating system for the house, unique for the time, with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Her 45-degree tilt seems a bit bizarre.
In his work, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> consistently ignored all the building regulations of that time and did not let himself be distracted by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he gave about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified at the completion of the project that they demanded a remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also came across the fact that the construction with its pillars even interfered with the public sidewalk.
However, there were no more changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the request of the district in this regard, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> submitted an application for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a parlor, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
However, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could comfortably chat without having to forgo a certain intimacy during more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s renovation also gave the house a rather unusual roof and two other floors.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s play with the light and the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is clad and the atriums are also impressive.
The play of these two colors gives a maximum of light to all floors of the house.
In doing so, he simply used the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can now be visited by anyone.
On the first floor is the most spacious and magnificent apartment open to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was discovered that this was a quite profitable business, the visits were kept, yes, they were also extended to other common and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price to visit the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon turrets, you should try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed frame? Women have different wishes than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
Many things play a role in the selection - the weight, the size, the state of health and not least the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior, in which mattress and rust have to subordinate themselves.
Typical example?
In a weekend house where there is no regular heating, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "get warm".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
If they do not have enough venting ducts in the core and lie on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is therefore not impossible that mold will form under them.
Of course, the choice also depends on what you are used to.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will find it difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"Well, all the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained to me that they can't sleep here anymore."
"For their chapped shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (memory foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I recommend these, among other things, to sugar-sick people who suffer from a disorder of the nervous system, so that they can receive the "information" from the joints and the skin poorly," explains Sylva Hadamczikov<0xC3><0xA1>, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That’s why years ago I bought many ice hockey players, but also other customers, these mattresses with visco foam (memory foam).
"Today, this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses offer, among others, the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don’t necessarily have to be a famous hockey player to appreciate the benefits of visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it really nestles on the warm body.
Nowhere is it pressing, at night you don’t roll around like after a hard fight.
You just sleep much better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against pressure ulcers (wound burn).
When choosing the mattress size, you should still add to the body size the length of the soles of the feet, so about 21 to 34 cm.
Both men and women, who are about 180 cm tall, need such a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each of the sleepers should have at least 90 cm of lying width available, so together 180 cm.
For single beds, for example, for singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For comfort and also for potential visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough space for the slightly angled arms," advises Ing. Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>, the guild master of upholsterers and interior designers, who has been dedicated to the problem of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture for years and who also talks about this topic at specialist schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own grate and mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are the same height.
Otherwise, there is no choice but to mount the gratings at different heights and this is by no means possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be accounted for by the molding layer and the fine padding.
"By hand or when sitting down, you should not feel the feathers under any circumstances," warns Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and underlay like grown-up Siamese twins have nothing to do in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the cover cannot be washed, which is already common practice today.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged sieve).
This is another reason why professionals reject advertising slogans that promise a lifespan of up to 25 years, even a lifetime warranty, for mattresses.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: With mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, you should not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, but it is still recommended to use a mattress protector, which can be easily peeled off and washed.
Even though today, mattress covers are usually made with a wrap-around zipper, so that after opening you get two halves (immensely important for the washing process and the size of the washing machine!), the manipulation with larger mattresses, especially executed alone, often seems like the unequal struggle between David and Goliath.
Do they have a fixed plate in bed instead of a grate?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Even so, they should rather provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there are none in it) and mattresses with spring skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring core and fine padding.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a base.
For non-adjustable slatted frames with 14 to 18 slats (slats) latex or sandwich mattresses are suitable (possibly also combinations of latex and coconut), always slatted frames with a larger number of slats, i.e. 28 and more slats pay off, with lumbar support in the lumbar region and the possibility to regulate the slat hardness.
On adjustable slatted gratings do not include mattresses with spring skeleton, as they do not respond to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the spring slats, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring slats, which makes it possible to press in the spring slats or even to angle them in such a way that they make it possible for the shoulder of the sleeper to sink at points.
Especially for men with wide shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started to use soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic leaf spring systems (Lattoflex) or grates with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multitorsion spring systems are intended.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too large and full) pillow for the right mattress and proper grate, most of the benefits will be lost again.
Again, a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach up to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Therefore, a 50 x 60 cm pillow, as the Scandinavians like it, seems ideal.
In the side position, the pillow (along with the shoulder relief zone in the grate or the soft zone in the mattress) should balance the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former straw bags (filled with hay).
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
Even with mattresses, the new magic word is "organic".
Instead of crude oil raw materials, natural oils are increasingly used for the production of polyurethane foams - for example castor oil and soybean oil.
Soy is probably used by all known manufacturers.
"Bio is the name given to mattresses, whose core consists of materials of purely natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek of Tropico Plus.
However, natural materials are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
However, you can also treat yourself to microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scents when you sleep.
Again, there is a difference between a man and a woman.
While in men, a "cooling" plant extract from birch leaves is used so that the mattress cover can absorb the heat and cool the body, for women, the covers have a "warming" effect.
Extracts of red peppers stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex becomes pleasantly warm when sleeping.
And today's favorites?
Mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercially available polyurethane and also much more flexible).
By combining the different stiffness (hardness) of cold foams and visco foams, multi-zone mattresses are created that know exactly where the head, hips and heels are located.
