Longer index finger than ring finger means lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index fingers are longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is said to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty," said Ros Eeles, a co-author of the study, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic risks or other risk factors are present, such as family health burdens, added Ms. Eeles.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but at the same time 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer was considered, as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which are already formed at prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
V<0xC3><0xA1>clav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, a leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told <0xC4><0x8C>TK that he was aware of the study, but did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be “fully proven”.
