The democracy movement in Latin America is growing stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil’s influence is greater than that of the United States.
These were the results of the Latinobar<0xC3><0xB3>metro survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year’s September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased strongly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing at an annual rate of about 6% since 2002, the number of pro-democracy voters has risen from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend is also evident in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the sharp slump last year.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country’s democratic practices, as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
Some 34% trust their country’s Congress and 45% trust their government, both of which are the same as last year, but show a significant increase over 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
The fact that this continued during the Great Depression may be due to the fact that Latin American countries experienced only a brief period of recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only marginally in 2009 and fell by 32% again this year.)
However, there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see diagram 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more perceptible and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see diagram 5).
About 31% say that either they or a family member was the victim of a crime last year, but down from 38% last year, the figures are at their lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic output is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economies: around 71% of respondents nationwide indicated that the private sector is indispensable for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% stated that only the market economy can bring their country progress, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private economy), even though their left-wing president, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, nationalizes many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, see the US as the most influential country, with Venezuela assuming this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
