After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light for a new start.
A New York bankruptcy judge on Thursday officiated the "preparatory" bailout plan to pay off $5 billion in debt and pave the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company's new films and television shows.
According to Thursday’s statements, the plan meets the requirements of U.S. bankruptcy law, so there is nothing standing in the way of MGM’s restart under the direction of Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, the founders of Spyglass Entertainment. Barber and Birnbaum will lead the somewhat slimmed-down studio as CEOs.
The number of employees will be reduced from over 400 to about 320.
For MGM, Chapter 11 does not actually enter into force until JPMorgan Chase has completed a planned $500 million bond to finance the new MGM productions.
At the moment, a consortium of the investment bank, which itself generates $75 million, is leading the company. The financing is expected to be by mid-December.
The reorganization of the studio began in May 2009 with an order from the investment bank Moelis & Co, the management of the company, which struggled with interest payments amounting to $300 million/year, to help solve its financial problems.
In August, Managing Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO at Enron and restructuring expert who became known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis & Cooper’s efforts to resolve MGM’s financial concerns and pay off the studio’s more than 140 creditors took longer than expected.
After months of discussions, the parties decided at the end of 2009 to offer the company for sale.
But the auction attracted only a few bidders and no one wanted to pay the $2 billion demanded by the creditors.
In the spring of this year, everything started all over again when the MGM team began the restructuring plan, which was finally signed by the creditors at the end of October after months of debate and internal disputes.
If MGM has officially survived bankruptcy in the next few weeks, Moelis and Cooper will receive a bonus of several million dollars for their work.
The share for Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, amounts to $9.5 million.
Cooper, who was paid $375,000 a month to run the company, will receive a “success bonus” of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM. This year, the studio released only one film and made an annual schedule of seven or eight films, which are expected to hit theaters in early 2012.
In addition, they are planning two films after "The Little Hobbit" in co-production with Warner Bros.
The studio needs a separate bond of $265 million to $275 million for its financial stake in these two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who funded about 18% of the MGM loan, attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, of which he is the largest shareholder.
However, the last negotiations between the two companies did not lead to any results.
Tech Toys keeps your gift budget in balance
This year’s favorite gift is the iPad, possibly followed by a Microsoft Kinect video console, both of which can make a sizable hole in your gift budget.
An iPad costs as much as five BMX wheels for $99, while the price for a Kinect game is about 10 classic jump ropes or about 48 cans of Play-Doh.
But you can save your gift budget.
Recently, looking for three electronic toys under $80, I visited three national toy retailers - a Wal-Mart, a Toys "R" Us, and a BJ's Wholesale Club.
I immediately realized that Moore’s law had come into force. This year the technology toys are more powerful and at the same time cost a little less than last year.
And although fewer new toys appear with their own website, the best-known of this kind, Webkinz and Club Penguin, has a wider range.
More and more button-cell-powered toys are coming to market, and many contain rechargeable batteries.
Here are some recommendations.
(Unless otherwise stated, all prices are from Toys "R" Us.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13, for children from 3 years) are plush figures, the size of guinea pigs that sing a note when you press on their stomachs.
Pressing once corresponds to a note, by pressing several times you can play a song.
Several sing-a-ma-jigs sing in harmony.
Attention: Once you have started pressing, you can no longer stop.
For a combination of text and dance, the Dance Star Mickey (Fisher price $60, for children from 2) is the best choice.
Based on the Elmo Live technology developed last year, the animatronic doll offers interplays like 'Simon Says', and thanks to its novel wheel-locked hinged feet, it masters the Moon Walk.
Kids who tested the device use Mickey as a dance instructor, but their parents complained about the lack of volume control.
If you’re an 80s kid, you certainly remember Alfie, one of the first computerized learning toys.
Now he's back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40, for children from 3), with a bunch of question cards that can turn a car ride into a lesson, with a know-it-all with autocorrect function as a teacher.
If you don’t want to entrust your smartphone to your child, here are three independent alternatives.
VTech’s MobiGo ($60 for kids ages 3 to 8) is the cheapest and most user-friendly solution, equipped with a qwerty keyboard, but the games on it aren’t as educational as those on the Leapster Explorer ($70, for kids ages 3 to 12), which features a new, brighter screen after Leapfrog’s first major overhaul of the Leapster series.
None of the versions is compatible with older cassettes.
Fisher-Price’s iXL ($90 for kids ages 3 to 7) uses a system similar to iTunes for the games and eBooks, and thanks to the SD card drive, family photos can also be viewed on it.
Last but not least, there is Scrabble Flash ($30 from Hasbro, for children from 8). The five blocks are no bigger than a matchbox and have their own LED screen.
The game is all about collapsing the blocks into words before time runs out and is great for an improvised spelling contest.
More and more toys have some kind of online connection.
If you go to the toy stores alone after the offer, Webkinz and Club Penguin are the most important.
For example, to give your child an online animal at Club Penguin, you can buy a Disney Club Penguin 2" Mix 'N Match Figure Pack ($5 for children from 6 to 12) that contains a coin with a secret code.
If you enter the code online, your child will receive enough credits for two more parts in the Club Penguin Store.
These can be roller skates or a Puffle stuffed animal.
The latest head-cell-powered microrobot, Hexbug Nano ($10 for kids 5+) is no bigger than the head of your toothbrush.
The beetle moves quickly on 12 vibrating silicone legs in any direction.
It's fun to send him through a maze of blocks.
And he holds out a lot.
Ours fell off the kitchen table and even survived for some time in the mouth of our dog.
Police operations in China are getting softer
Like a training officer, Tang Shenbin stepped over an urban square, checking his nervous subordinates, issuing orders with military authority and muted voice.
He wanted his female members of the Chengguan—China’s robust guardians of the urban order, feared and despised for their arbitrary raids and their propensity for violence—to impress viewers.
"Stand straight!"
"Look straight ahead!"
"Show them," he whispered to them, "how pretty girls are like that!"
Four girls, barely outgrown their teenage years, with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and pants, stood tight.
Four pairs of black pumps stood in a straight line.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue and white striped bows.
"To me, they look average," Mr. Tang remarks contemptuously.
"Models are beautiful."
Several governments have already tried to polish up the image of China’s city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
Guangdong Province introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the grey-green one.
Wuhan in central China replaced violence with stares: In 2009, 50 officials reportedly circled an improperly set-up food truck and stared at the operator until he packed up after half an hour and left the place.
Xindu, a city district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have reinforced the urban police patrols and have been specially selected for their appearance, their good figure and their youth.
They are meant to give the rough-and-tumble police a softer, feminine aspect.
Unfortunately, Scarlett Johansson would not be able to improve the bad image the Chinese have of these city commands.
And rightly so, the critics.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce city laws through fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely shows a different picture.
In January 2008, officials in Hubei province beat a spectator to death when he filmed them using his mobile phone as they crushed a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual of Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how offenders can be beaten without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon trader suffered brain injuries after a scuffle with five officials.
A violent video game that can be downloaded from the Internet shows officials trained in China in an attack on street vendors.
"Chengguan scares the government," the national newspaper China Daily lamented last year, after further controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for a “really thorough clean-up.”
Skeptics consider the current approach to be significantly inadequate.
When the district searched for eight female recruits via ad in October, an editorial in the Beijing Evening News asked whether the women had real tasks or should only serve as an optical distraction.
Probably both.
According to the job advertisement, women aged 18 to 22 with a good figure and "harmonious facial features" were sought.
They should be above average in size - about 1.5m or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
The employment relationship ends at the age of 26.
According to the officials, the activity is too strenuous for women over 25.
"The most important thing is their image," said an unnamed district official at the quasi-government website Rednet.com.
"Whether the candidates get the job depends first on their outward appearance, such as height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes temperament and “inner qualities.”
“Female Chengguan are like flower vases,” he said, adding, “but beyond that, they have other duties.”
Zheng Lihua, deputy head of the district’s municipal administration, does not agree with this description,
But admitted that in China, size limits in job ads for both genders are not uncommon.
The same applies to uniform facial features.
Whether this can be equated with good looks is controversial in China.
But people with disabilities or physical deformities do not need to apply.
"Unfortunately, we can't use lame or humpbacks here," Mr. Zheng said.
"Your image would not be good."
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22, has apple pies and a well-shaped mouth.
She didn’t feel sexist that she was so attached to her appearance.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asks with an ironic look.
Her colleague with the dimples, 21-year-old Xu Yang, comments, "We have the task to represent the image of the city."
According to them, they do not regret the short attitude, as they have more ambitious career plans than just scare traders through the alleys to prevent them from doing business.
Every morning, the patrol deals with about twelve street vendors who try to sell as many rolls and tofu dishes as possible on foot or by bicycle before they are chased away.
"Mr. Wang, please get out of here."
"We've told you this so many times!" explains Frl. Xu to a merchant who had fled on foot and had temporarily abandoned his pasta kitchen, which was attached to a bicycle cart.
According to the officials, the activity is monotonous rather than exhausting.
“It’s almost the same every day,” explains Huang Jing, 20, who studies sales in the leisure industry.
"Everything routine."
One reason for this is that the female officials are not allowed to confiscate the traders’ goods, like their male counterparts.
They can only threaten offenders by reporting them to their male superiors.
This is to protect them from public hostility, which officials in China are often exposed to.
This year, hundreds of residents of Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, rioted after rumors circulated that Chengguan officials had killed a trader.
More than a dozen police officers and Chenguan officials were injured in the nighttime incident, 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
Xindu has been spared such violence so far.
But unrest cannot be ruled out.
Just two blocks away from the quiet Baonguang Square where female officers patrolled that morning, over 50 people gathered at a street corner.
Officials had confiscated a motorcycle, which was repaired on the sidewalk instead of in a workshop, contrary to the regulations.
The owner shouted Zeter and Mordio.
After 15 minutes of hesitation, the officers made their way to their vehicles with a grim face and continued with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a male patrol coordinator, stayed behind, flipping his white name tag to remain anonymous.
Like her colleagues, the coordinators - men over 40 - play a purely supportive role.
But they were not trained to present a clean image.
“Sometimes we go verbal.”
"Sometimes, but also physically," Mr. Li explains soberly.
“Most of the time, people start fighting.”
Prosecutors will not indict Senator Ensign
Attorneys at the Department of Justice have acquitted Senator John Ensign of the charges made against him after his affair with a former election worker and his attempt to get her husband to lobby, the senator’s lawyers announced Wednesday.
This decision ends the most serious lawsuit against Senator Ensign, the Republican from Nevada. Until the scandal, which made national headlines and put a damper on his career, he was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012.
As Senator Ensign’s office announced, he was “highly pleased” with the verdict after the one-year investigation.
However, the Senate Ethics Committee could still impose a disciplinary penalty.
According to Ensign’s attorneys, they were informed by the Department of Justice that the investigation into Senator Ensign had been terminated and that there were no further charges on the matter.
The Justice Department did not comment on the case.
The ruling came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who believe there was sufficient evidence that Ensign violated the lobbying ban.
Interviews, e-mails, and other documents first disclosed in the New York Times in October 2009 gave rise to the suspicion that Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, one of his election aides, to lucrative contracts to buy his silence over an affair with Hampton’s wife Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as treasurer during an Ensigns election campaign.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton to work, and according to the records and interrogations, he took over Hampton's lobbying for them after the hiring.
Since Hampton was recently on Ensign’s election team, he was not allowed to lobby for his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called ban on the revolving-door lobbyocracy.
According to the published evidence, “it appears to be an arrangement and violation of the revolving door statutes,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients targeted by the government.
While the Department of Justice officially declined to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the Department appears to be very cautious in taking political charges after a variety of defeats pursued by the media with great interest, including last year’s decision to drop the charges against former Senator Ted Stevens for misconduct on the part of the prosecutor.
Prosecutors “are obviously horrifying,” said Melanie Sloan, the chairman of the Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington association (an organization whose goal is to fight corruption in U.S. parliamentary and government circles), a group of lawyers who have brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to court.
“This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws don’t apply to them,” she added.
Paul Coggins, chief defense attorney for Mr. Ensign, said in an interview that he had received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another the next day informing him that the ministry would not bring any lawsuits against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defense attorneys had cooperated with prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, had "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to explain in more detail the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of the conversation between the Department of Justice and me, just to be clear, we think we've made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Electoral Commission decided to close the investigation into a separate lawsuit by the ethics group, according to which a $96,000 payment from Mr. Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated federal electoral law.
The election commission said there was not enough evidence that the money was anything other than a gift.
NV Energy, a large company in Nevada that long supported the Senator, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found lobbyist work thanks to the help of Mr. Ensign.
An e-mail from December 2008 shows that after the company moved Mr. Hampton forward as lobbyist, Mr. Ensing's chief of staff, John Lopez, had a conversation with Mr. Hampton in which he told him that he was "knocking" at the Home Office about a case.
Mr. Ensign also met with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, for lunch, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after Mr. Hampton had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When information about this affair first surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and gave up his position in the Senate, where he ranked fourth among Republicans.
After many months of noticing, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of police investigation, his press secretary, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hopes the ethics committee will very quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and stop its investigation.
“Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work in the service of the people of Nevada,” she said.
Cheshire appeal draws attention to Twitter
Half a dozen of them tipped away in the riots in the courtroom.
Every minute, they sent their reports of gruesome witness statements via Twitter.
In the end, according to the defense, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the process of rape and children chained to beds in a house that went up in flames.
On Thursday, the closely watched trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was accused of killing three members of a family from Cheshire, Connecticut, will find an official end when the verdict on the death sentence pronounced by the jury falls.
However, Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have already filed motions in court that state the reasons for an appeal and that will keep the courts busy for years to come.
One of the most provocative reasons is that the intense coverage of the process – including the extensive use of Twitter by average reporters – has resulted in a “circus atmosphere” and such widespread, immediate penetration of seditious details that the jury has been unduly influenced by public outrage.
This objection could lead the appellate courts to consider whether the new technologies make new rules necessary in the courtroom.
"Just as I experienced it during this trial, I believe that it is really a danger if the entry of new technologies into the courtroom affects the right of every individual to a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullman, Mr. Hayes' chief defense attorney.
The presiding judge, Jon C. Blue of the Supreme Court of Appeal, succinctly rejected the motions by decision last week when he said the New Media would be “carefully controlled” and that there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passions.
But that was certainly not the last word on the matter.
For decades, court filings have found that reporting on infamous cases casts doubt on the fairness of a trial.
In its historic 1966 decision, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the ruling against Dr. Sam Sheppard, an osteopath from Cleveland who is said to have killed his wife, saying in his decision that there had been a “carnival atmosphere in the courtroom” because of the New Media.
Some believe that the television series and the feature film "Auf der Flucht" is based on this crime.
Some lawyers say court appeals, which Mr. Hayes' conviction looks at half a century later, could follow the argument that new rules have become necessary to regulate the lines of communication from the courtroom that were unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
“There’s a good reason to be concerned about the influence of the new media in trials being pursued by a broad public,” said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who investigated the death penalty in Connecticut.
Professor Donohue said some appellate courts may be intrigued by the idea that restricting immediate communication out of the courtroom could make the processes fairer.
