Some of the jurors have said photos of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48 years old, and her suitor, Hayley, 17 years old, and Michaela, 11 years old, had filled them with disgust.
Defendants say they also question the constitutionality of the death penalty constitution, arguing that the judge mistakenly exchanged a juror who had been a critic of the prosecution, and that he unduly put pressure on the verdict when he made the unusual decision to release the jury over the weekend.
The jurors were not isolated.
But their arguments about the influence of detailed reporting on the process may attract the greatest interest.
In a judgment challenge they filed last month, they found that the case had dominated the news in Connecticut and was being debated by candidates during the campaign for governor and for the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the New Media had continuously rekindled the flames of emotion about the case.
“Such a daily influx of media pimps, cameras and reporters outside the courtroom,” the lawyers wrote, “has not been experienced before in New Haven and perhaps even nationwide.”
Her focus on Twitter reporting is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists said that the claim that these direct messages are more inflammatory than reports that are being relayed more slowly is a technology-haunting look that impoverishes reporting on future processes.
But some lawyers said appellate courts would often face the argument that societal and technical changes required adaptation by the courts.
Mr. Hayer's lawyers reinforce this claim.
In their objection, they referred to the Supreme Court decision of 1966, in which Dr. Sheppard’s conviction was overturned on the basis of reporting, and made it clear that the New Media required new rules.
“This case,” they wrote, “represents Sheppard against Maxwell of the 21st century.”
Can courtesy connect the divider?
After a campaign of rants and negativity, little courtesy has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of genuine two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before quickly returning to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring a breakthrough in the big questions that were addressed during the so-called “lame duck session,” the session at the end of a government period in which no more decisions are made.
After all that one hears, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor a consideration of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of partisan scoring.
The public meeting of the president’s deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue to exist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to divide members.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a testing phase - in which one demands from the other sign of cooperation and willingness to compromise, while one tries to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of the voters after a new party warfare.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it is about taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, Washington’s November election has been mild for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone of voice has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections awaken partisan passions that are dying off again.
And that's a good thing."
On some issues, especially those on the Lame Duck Session agenda, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one is advocating that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or even all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Likewise, a compromise on the increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe that the favored tax cuts for the rich are being made while they deny support to unemployed workers.
After the meeting on Tuesday in the White House, the optimism has risen that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session "does not necessarily lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical—and this skepticism is shared by many—that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what is happening from now until 2012 as pre-fight, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have much to do with the appearance of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their formation.
No matter how concerned Republican leaders may be about poker being too high, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and override health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as the raising of the retirement age and the lowering of government spending.
Vice Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own assessment, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation and they are struggling very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the panel, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will take place next year in the form of party clashes when Republicans challenge Obama regarding the state budget, taxes, and health care system, followed later by a phase of greater two-party cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanism and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and the Congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a much wider election in 2012.
Seen in this light, the courtesy displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that still separate the two.
Leaked US document portrays Moscow as a port of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of the “Kleptocracy” and it passes on some of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, the American Embassy in Russia reported in a memo in February.
Both the police and the State Security Service are extorting high protection funds so that they can maintain their expensive standard of living in Moscow, it is said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal gangs.
Every layer of the bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical of authority” – takes its share of the money that moves the ladder upwards.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted on his homepage by WikiLeaks on Tuesday.
The memo is based on sources whose names have been edited.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still Moscow’s mayor, and it accuses him of corruption.
He was fired by President Dmitry Medvedev in October, but there is little evidence that has since been cleared up.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have repeatedly denied allegations of corruption for years, and he has won numerous libel suits against such accusations.
In September, he told a Russian television station when asked about a documentary that suggested he was corrupt: “It’s crazy, it’s dirty, it’s dirty.”
> An incredibly large number of Russians believe that their society is corrupt, according to polls.
But it is unusual that, as happened in the ambassador's report, individuals are called, and it is unheard of that this is done by a diplomat of a foreign country.
"The direct link between the Moscow government and crime has led some to call it 'disturbed' and conclude that the government is acting more like a kleptocrat than a government," the memo said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘kryshna’ (a term from the world of criminals/mafia, which literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that extends across the police, State Security (FSB), Service Supervision Authority (MVD) and Prosecutor’s Office as well as the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have discovered a three-layered structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luchkov is at the top."
"FSB, MVD and the militia are on the second stage."
"Finally, the ordinary criminals and the criminal inspectors follow at the lowest level."
“This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas because the city does not offer any help.”
The report goes on to say that the FSB is collecting money from the largest companies and that the police are arresting small businessmen.
A source, it is said, “explained that Moscow’s business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime), because they not only have more weapons, resources and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by the law.”
"For this reason, protection by criminal gangs is no longer as in demand as it used to be."
The memo notes that while collecting funds is comprehensive, the protection itself may not be very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who do not pay find their business closed very quickly - due to one or the other pretext.
Medvedev has spoken several times about fighting corruption, but at the same time has noted that he has made little progress.
The memo of the embassy contains descriptions of men who go to the Kremlin with suitcases that were probably full of money.
“In his fight against corruption, Medvedev must rely on the bureaucrats,” Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow commission of experts, said in a recent interview.
"But he's part of that bureaucracy."
"It is not part of the political class, because a political class no longer exists in Russia."
Without politicians, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationwide, Indem estimates, corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country is ranked 154th in a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are listed from “least corrupt” to “most corrupt”).
The unveiling of the memo of the American embassy, which happened late at night after Moscow’s time, will certainly cause displeasure within the Russian government, although, since Luzhkov can be accused of Moscow’s mistakes, it can also be a way for the Kremlin to claim that one solves the problems.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fake and reacted furiously to the revelation that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth is that it’s about our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic politics in this country,” he said.
"But to be honest, we didn't expect this to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure, and in such a unethical way, you know."
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to confront the past
In a dimly lit, concrete classroom with dirty and peeling walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School remembers the man who built it, the future Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years old.
Because of his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule known as "the butcher", the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed infrastructure and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge capitulation to the government, longtime supporters in Anlong Veng are being challenged.
In April, a local Truth and Reconciliation Forum allowed victims to publicly confront the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a textbook that tells the story of the Khmer Rouge to children of former soldiers for the first time.
And in July, a UN and Cambodian community tribunal first sentenced a former member of the Khmer Rouge when it sentenced former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear grew among Khmer Rouge veterans Alnlong Vengs, hampering their efforts at reconciliation and reintegration into Cambodian society.
“There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, head of Cambodia’s documentation center, an independent organization that researches the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
“It divides families.”
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of disease, overwork or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and the Pol Pot-Id government collapsed in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary waged guerrilla warfare from their base in the west of the mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok drew up the next generation in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, leading to the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died a natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not given in, was arrested by government forces at the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh prison in 2006, awaiting trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled into the grueling poverty of rural Cambodia and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Even though a few elite Khmer Rouge officials kept their local government posts because they laid down their weapons, the ordinary soldiers remained poor, uneducated peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are anchored in the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Rhmer Rouge in 1974 as a teenager, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settling down in 1998 to live a life as a poor rice farmer.
“Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,” he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
“But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves.”
The ongoing Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also raised concerns here.
Early next year, the court will try to bring to justice Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, as well as Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The order of the court is to condemn the old leaders and those mainly responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will pursue further acts beyond these four cases.
This has done little to alleviate fears in Anlong Veng.
Current media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who had been district chief in Manteay Meanchey Province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told the Cambodian Documentation Centre that she was in charge of the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced labourers are believed to have died.
One hot evening, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty street outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the withered grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss her past at the Khmer Rouge.
Should the court summon her, she would refuse to leave, she said.
“Cambodia lives in peace and stability,” she said.
"If there were no more persecutions, there would be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that if the situation became uncertain, the court would indict more suspects, although experts and historians discuss this.
“Cambodia needs to dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do in order to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Centre.
"Reconciliation with the Khmer times means gathering the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken parts together so that as everything can understand."
The center created the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia."
It distributed the book in June in Anlong Veng as an appendix to the Ministry of Education's High School History Book, which contains fewer than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
As is often the case in Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents were skeptical when he brought the book home to read.
"My family rejects many parts of the book and the court," he said.
"They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people will be convicted by the court."
Such resistance makes the reconciliation process complex and complicated, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court gradually gain influence," he said.
The Khmer Rouge still has a powerful attraction here.
At the top of the Dangrek Mountains, a path overgrown with shrubs and polluted with plastic waste leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty sheet metal roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31 years old, a mobile phone saleswoman on the side of the road, said she didn’t know much about the man who had been burned here.
