Red Bull wins in F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
The cars are improved with real-time software.
Ever since Red Bull entered the world of Formula One in 2004, its history in this exquisite universe of speed has been marked by surprises and successes.
In the beginning, nobody paid attention to the newcomer and despite his steeply rising career during the last seasons, in the final sprint last November, everyone was counting on the victory of the Ferrari of Fernando Alonso.
Without degrading the skills of the German driver and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of the Renault engine, the "secret weapon" that the Multi Siemens Red Bull put in its hands, and thus created a winning team, has become a legend.
In reality, it is a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched in 2007 for non-auto racing purposes.
This computer program, known as PLM, was used for the development of assembly chains in factories around the world, energy plants and high-precision instruments.
The aim is a faithful reproduction or simulation of a product or process before it is actually built in order to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon’s cameras, Sukhoi’s aircraft and Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industry department at Siemens, explains that with the use of this software in the Formula 1 factory Red Bull "in a few hours, almost in real time" can design and execute the changes and improvements that are detected on the races and in the tests.
Russwurm states that in 1992, an average of ten technicians worked in the race stables, who could introduce a maximum of three or four improvements in a season.
Today, Red Bull’s team employs 180 highly qualified young people, who carry out analyses and make all kinds of changes to the race car with high-performance IT systems.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all components of Red Bull’s racing cars, with the exception of the engine for which Renault is solely responsible.
The materials, the fuel, the aerodynamics and the safety elements are changed.
Thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves, the changes can be transferred from the virtual reality of the simulator into reality within less than 24 hours.
The only limit set to this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million a Formula 1 team is allowed to spend on its races in a season.
Red Bull has built its high-tech factory for the development and manufacture of its racing cars in a location 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings in which visits - especially by journalists - are strongly restricted.
Everything that happens there is top secret.
The crew consists of 580 people, including the two pilots, the world champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull’s true Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly the newest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the energy drink manufacturer places in the service of its participation on the race tracks, there are other protagonists, whose support is invaluable and whose fame equals zero.
The plant’s technologist, Steve Nevey, points out that five years ago, it was still possible to say that the progress in R&D for racing cars contributed with 50 percent to the victory and the pilots were responsible for the rest.
Today, the share values have changed. The technology accounts for 85 percent of the success, while the contribution of the pilots is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by EDP because they "are unpredictable gladiators."
