Zapatero and the Red Line of Germany
Berlin decided to keep the euro, but at the same time set conditions for the entire European Union.
Tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, starting with tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment companies or the cancellation of the €426 support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, up to the privatization of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, Deputy Prime Minister Elena Salgado, with the help of former President Felipe Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It should be assumed that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which collides with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, people in Germany are beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction -, supported by a large part of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a reshaping of the euro according to German proposals, which means more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that exceed the requirements; possibly the suspension of payments of some countries, as well as the extension of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled out of its sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country, as Merkel painfully pushed out the decision to rescue Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the public opinion were absolutely opposed to a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again comes out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the agreements of the European Union to enable the rescue of a country and at the same time to oblige private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it pushed forward the Irish crisis and everything else.
In the coming months, we will take part in the reform of the European Union, which will make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures now have to be taken - from this date the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the infringing countries can be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent, and in this case the private sector has to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to pursue a hard growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness as well as positive external economic balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as it was led by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It is not just a question of reducing the state deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will pass more calmly.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities we are offered by spring 2013.
Zapatero seems to have understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own home has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like it would change anything.
Among the possibilities under consideration, we cannot rule out the fact that we would have to leave the euro area, which is full of less serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it had warned us.
Sport and rule circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match against Ajax in the Champions League on 23 November resulted in a lot of ink being shed over whether it was an unsportsmanlike act or not and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the prescribed sanction at the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next phase of the game without cards.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos – the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the debate surrounding the case that emerged stems from the fact that a team from the Real Madrid football club (who pretended to be noble and honored in his anthem and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead role, and the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether this behaviour, which is expressly prohibited by the statutes, does not contradict the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a rule circumvention.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sportsmanship defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from drawing an unjustified benefit from the opposing team, which did not happen either.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by foul play or rule circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and happily accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the intentional fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was neither placed in a more unfavorable position nor required advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue to play with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it’s a long-term, up to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually drop out, as well as giving players a sanction and moving into the second card cycle, where they drop out less than in the first cycle due to card aggregation.
It is not clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to derive the greatest possible benefit from the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they wanted to rather choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without resorting to punishment or fleeing it.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and control environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemic arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these acts is less ethical than aesthetic.
