On the hunt for WikiLeaks boss
Obama appoints a high-ranking official for the anti-terrorism campaign to prevent new revelations.
Interpol issued a red alert to the persecution and discovery of Assange.
Everything related to WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated labyrinth in which the facts are difficult to clarify.
Yesterday, Interpol issued a "red warning" about the "finding and persecution" of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
It’s not new, it’s dated November 20.
It also has nothing to do with the latest revelation of over four million diplomatic documents from the US, but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian has to face in Sweden.
The WikiLeaks founder’s lawyer, Mark Stephens, said the police “know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.”
Already on the 20th, the international police authority based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but it was not announced until yesterday after receiving the authority by the Swedish authorities.
The 188 Interpol countries are instructed to identify and locate Assange "in order to provisionally arrest and extradite him."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, according to the organization, many member states consider the red alert to be a carte blanche for an arrest — which must be carried out by the national police — especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case of Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be present.
The move outraged Assange’s lawyers, who yesterday published a letter informing them that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks is ready to answer Swedish authorities’ questions via video conference.
They also remind that Assange applied for leave from Sweden and received the appropriate approval from the prosecutor, who is compared to the fabled Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin’s security chief.
“This is like a hunt, not a legal prosecution,” the letter said.
While the world is looking for him – and his mother from Australia asserts her son’s innocence – Assange is in an unknown place, but not in silence.
On Monday, he gave an interview to Time magazine’s head via Skype from an unspecified location, requesting the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
“If it can be proven that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN and thus violate international agreements signed by the US, she would have to resign,” he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who described the request for resignation as "ridiculous and absurd."
“I’m not sure why we should value the opinion of a guy with a website,” he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a senior anti-terrorism campaigner, Rusell Travers, with preventing new document disclosures.
President Barack Obama’s attempt to pay less attention to Assange contrasts with the views expressed by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the National Security Committee of the House of Representatives from January, has called on the State Department to investigate the possibility of putting Wikileaks on the list of terrorist organizations "to confiscate their funds and prosecute anyone who supports them or makes a contribution."
Tom Flanagan, adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, had gone even further, and he had to retract his statement that Assange must be “murdered.”
"Obama would have to turn it into a target and use an unmanned plane or something."
