China maintains its targets to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of China said at COP16 that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and it would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China keeps its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16, assures.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Change Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said his country has invested $245 million over the last four years to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He explained that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year that includes the goals of reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the state authorities had worked with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, an effective use of energy and the reduction of emissions.
In addition, he said, several multi-year plans have already been initiated or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those receiving funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Effective Use of Energy programme, which was introduced over the last five years and had received investment from the United Nations (UN), government and private hands.
It is also running a provincial-level project on climate change, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, a scientific adviser on climate change in this country, confirmed that China’s efforts were far greater than was commonly assumed.
He showed that the per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to pollution.
Energy efficiency has increased by 20 percent in the last five years, and another is expected to be achieved by 2020, he said.
