The U.S. Changes the Rules for Obtaining a Visa
Before their meeting with the consulate, the persons must present themselves to the service points for visa application; costs will be reduced in this way.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants have to present themselves to the Visa Application Services (ASC) before speaking at the consulate.
The personnel of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced because it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counter-value to 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for hands and investors.
Those who just want to extend their visa do not need to have a conversation in the consulate, they just need to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
As the biometric data is obtained in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment to speak at the consulate stay there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the service surcharge of 26 dollars.
Additional information on the new visa application process can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
