The find will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington, D.C., by astrobiology experts, a science that examines the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the universe.
In convening the press conference, NASA assured that it would present “a supervisory finding for the search for extraterrestrial life,” sparking speculation among experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that human-like creatures could exist in hostile environments that were previously thought to be uninhabitable, and it has been hypothesized that they could transform into intelligent living beings – just like humans – if their living conditions improved.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was considered too toxic for all life forms because the lake is highly arsenic.
In some way, the microbie uses arsenic as a survival resource, and taking this ability into account, it increases the chances that there could be similar life on other planets that do not have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms metabolize arsenic, according to astrobiologists, it is proven that “there is actually another life form, a second life form, which is different from what we know.”
The space agency will announce the actual reach of its find at the press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars, and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who studies Titan (Saturn’s largest moon) to see if its chemical composition is similar to that of Earth.
