Global lighting renewal plan
In Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction, which is almost one-third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilise the Earth’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs released to the earth due to lighting would be avoided if the white-hot bulbs, which so far still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better still, light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emissions emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, one would have to subtract 5 Gt from this balance to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-hot bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED light bulbs this energy requirement is reduced by twofold.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6,000 and 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those launched by Philips this week – this company, by the way, participated in the UN study – have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, suggesting the potential savings of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that completely new incandescent bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless producers provide a collection point.
