Métro Grand Paris: first financial sketches
Since the debate on the modernisation of the transport industry on the Ile-de-France is in full swing, it has rained billions.
At least in the discussions.
It is worth remembering in particular the 23 billion for the Metro Grand Paris, which is to be built by the Société du Grand Paris.
In order to initiate the start of construction of the SGP, the state has declared a capital endowment of 4 billion euros.
In the theoretical scheme, this is the sum which would then enable the SGP to lend a part of the financial sum twice as much in the markets.
Today, the first projections have finally been made.
The 2010 supplementary budget, reviewed this morning by the Finance Commission of the National Assembly, contains the measures envisaged to raise the first part of these funds.
These measures are twofold: the creation of a special tax for the development and higher taxation of offices in Ile-de-France.
The former, according to Article 15 of the bill, "goes in favor of the public-law institution Société du Grand Paris".
This is stated: "The product of this tax amounts to 117 million euros per year".
The second is a reorganization of the already existing corporate taxation: "to modernize it, to increase the resulting product and to hand over this increase to the Société du Grand Paris".
How much would that contribute?
A mystery.
This amount is not stated in the text.
Of the 4 billion, we are far away.
"It is stated that the tax resources will be added to the 4 billion euros of capital endowment raised by the state and will be gradually provided to the Société du Grand Paris for the project," the explanatory statement reads.
At the SGP, this system is not offensive at all.
"From the moment you book revenue (the two taxes, i.e.), you can cover the project planning for three years and then only draw from the 4 billion," it explains.
"This will be noted in the budget and gradually subtracted".
The SGP estimates that 2013 will begin to list the 4 billion for the 2014 budget.
This measure, of which 4 billion promised will be available for a long time, runs the risk of triggering quite a lively parliamentary debate.
The first public meeting will be held on 7 December.
vengeful hackers and busy spies
WikiLeaks has two meanings.
On the one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international level, and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's go one by one.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by an intelligence agency (an x-any nation) is made up entirely of newspaper clippings.
Berlusconi’s “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits throw in nothing more than what you’ve been reading for months anyway in any of his journals (except for those owned by Berlusconi), and the horrifyingly caricatured profile of Gaddafi has provided cabaret artists with material for their sketches for a long time.
The rule according to which the secret dossiers may consist only of already known news is essential for the dynamism of the intelligence services, and not only this century.
If you go to a library devoted to esoteric publications, you will realize that each work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism do not believe in anything other than what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown’s mechanism of success.
As well as the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited mind) is also the head of the secret service (otherwise, he could be whatever, for example, editor at Libération), who considers only what he acknowledges to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
Why, then, was such a fuss made about the disclosures of these dossiers?
On one side, these say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies – at least since the end of World War II and since then also the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner – have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representational tasks, have turned into espionage centers.
Any observer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that any hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
In addition, the scandal brings not so much the victims, but rather the "sharpeners" in distress.
But let’s focus on the profound nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s day, all power could be pooled like a Big Brother controlling every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy could have since turned out to be perfectly correct, where one can control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway chosen, and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if one considers what is going on today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker -- chosen as the citizen's avenger -- can learn the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets hold on?
True, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of Berlusconi’s or Merkel’s character is basically a secret free of secrecy, as it reveals the public sphere; but to disclose in the style of WikiLeaks that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty power secrets means to rob them of all.
WikiLeaks has done no injustice to Sarkozy or Merkel, but to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this insult inflicted on such a vast power?
It is obvious that in the future, the states will no longer put any reserved information online - this would be like a notice glued to the street corner.
But it is just as obvious that with the current technologies it is in vain to hope to be able to keep confidential reports over the phone secret.
Nothing is easier than figuring out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private and ear-only relationships be maintained in the future?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romance, but I am compelled to imagine the government agents, moving in a secret way busily on uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages nowhere but in mere memory, and, moreover, hiding the little written information they have received, in the heel of their shoes.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, Watergate’s spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is progressing like a cancer these days, namely backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructed a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analogous) videocassettes had enabled the film researchers to explore a film band by band, by winding from back to front and revealing all the secrets of the montage, while the (numerical) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro portions.
The high-speed trains run from Rome to Milan within three hours, while this takes three and a half hours by plane, including changing trains.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to return to cars and horses.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were being forged between the messages.
At present, it is the messages that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France makes good on its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the compliance of developing countries with the fast-fixed financing promises (also called "fast start" or premature financing).
And now the rough French fair speeches have been revealed.
Under the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn up all the registers to convince its partners of the fact of its commitment to fast-start funding: detailed progress report of its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
The transparency operation is remarkable and just appreciated for its intrinsic value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same on the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, setting it on the right track to paying respect to its commitment of 7.2 billion euros in 2012.
But when you look into the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional commitment was made without being detrimental to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline that they consider to be the best.
The European Commission, for example, has chosen to set a benchmark for 2009: international funding will be maintained, and it will add 150 million to the "Fast Start" funding over three years.
Other countries have adopted similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of official development assistance.
In return, France said that the financing of “all new projects” in 2010 was “new and additional.”
In other words, there are no benchmarks for expenditure in the previous year or at the global level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France claims to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule on this yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 borrowed € as the equivalent of 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often mitigation-related projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro that is collected as the equivalent of a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan to the investor country should be counted as commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans on a large scale.
Germany is demanding 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are making 100% of their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends 1€ to fulfil its obligations, France gives only 10 cents and understands a comparable commitment.
Beautiful hocus-pocus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double swindle: in part with a further development of the action over time and in part with the reality of financial commitment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; once in the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter of premature financing is only a small question for a relatively short period of time compared to the entirety of discussions on climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of early funding.
In the first place, France could announce a change in its accounting method for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and rebalancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could bring forward the discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another crucial issue that is currently under discussion): one cannot escape the question of "calculability" or the accounting method of its loans.
France could change its position to be as progressive on the issues as it is on other issues.
The hope is therefore based on the new environment minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France’s fast-start and its vision of “calculability” as well as the use of loans would inherently raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - Pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child consumes 81 different chemical substances over the course of the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Générations Futures Association (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which states that its results "given the small number of samples analysed, do not represent a statistically significant value, but rather illustrate the problem addressed", had bought between July and September the food usually consumed within four meals by a ten-year-old child, plus an intermediate meal in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals – including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products, and 1.5 liters of water per day – have been studied as well as lab-based snacks in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals, and other contaminants.
The plate balance is devastating: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as potentially or likely carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruptor, according to studies from several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded in the approximate totality of the cases, it is very clear from this survey that the reality in which the consumer may be exposed to carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine disruptor is worrying," notes the association.
At breakfast alone, the butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three that have been safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
In addition, the minced steak, the tuna from the can, even the baguette and the chewing gum were peppered with pesticides and other chemical substances.
In the case of tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 identified, chemical residues, and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unencumbered.
The ultimate risk of this “pollutant cocktail” for the consumer “is likely to be undervalued,” according to the study.
For its part, the Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed “in view of the urgency of the situation” to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the “increase in civilization diseases”.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
